---
export const prerender = true;

import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import EmailCapture from '../components/EmailCapture.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="From Coordination Tax to Coordination Layer — In Parallel" description="The hidden cost killing execution isn't strategy or talent — it's coordination. Here's how to turn it from a tax into an advantage.">
  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="pt-32 pb-16 md:pt-44 md:pb-24">
    <div class="container-ip max-w-4xl text-center">
      <p class="section-eyebrow mb-6 scroll-reveal">Coordination tax</p>
      <h1 class="font-display text-5xl md:text-7xl lg:text-headline tracking-tight leading-[0.95] mb-8 scroll-reveal">
        The hidden cost that kills execution &mdash; and how to eliminate it.
      </h1>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Preface -->
  <section class="pb-20 md:pb-32">
    <div class="container-ip">
      <div class="content-narrow scroll-reveal">
        <p class="text-white/85 font-display text-xl md:text-2xl leading-relaxed">
          Most organizations don&rsquo;t fail because of bad strategy or weak talent. They fail because <strong class="text-white">reality outpaces the plan, and no one notices until it&rsquo;s too late.</strong> Decisions happen in meetings, work happens in tools, and somewhere in the gap between the two, the shared picture of what&rsquo;s actually going on quietly falls apart. Managers end up filling that gap &mdash; chasing updates, reconciling versions, re-explaining things that were already decided &mdash; doing coordination work instead of the work that actually matters.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Pull quote -->
      <div class="content-narrow mt-16 mb-12 scroll-reveal">
        <p class="text-white font-display text-2xl md:text-3xl leading-snug">
          That invisible work is the coordination tax.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="content-narrow space-y-6 text-ip-white-muted text-lg leading-relaxed scroll-reveal">
        <p>
          It doesn&rsquo;t show up on a P&amp;L, but it consumes nearly half of every manager&rsquo;s week. Meetings become about reassurance, not decisions. Plans become theater. Progress depends less on execution and more on whether everyone still believes the same story.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Product screenshot break -->
  <section class="pb-20 md:pb-32">
    <div class="container-ip max-w-5xl scroll-reveal">
      <div class="relative rounded-2xl overflow-hidden border border-ip-border shadow-2xl shadow-black/40">
        <img
          src="/images/hero/hero-main.png"
          alt="In Parallel dashboard showing a living execution plan with priorities, decisions, and real-time status"
          class="w-full"
          loading="lazy"
        />
        <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-gradient-to-t from-ip-navy/60 via-transparent to-transparent pointer-events-none"></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The Evidence -->
  <section class="py-20 md:py-32 bg-ip-navy-light">
    <div class="container-ip">
      <div class="content-narrow text-center mb-16">
        <p class="section-eyebrow mb-4">The evidence</p>
        <h2 class="font-display text-3xl md:text-5xl tracking-tight mb-6">
          This isn't a theory. It's measurable.
        </h2>
      </div>

      <div class="content-narrow grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div class="bg-ip-navy-surface border border-ip-border rounded-xl p-8">
          <p class="font-serif text-5xl tracking-tight text-white/60 mb-3">58%</p>
          <p class="text-ip-white-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">of the workday goes to &ldquo;work about work&rdquo; &mdash; status updates, searching for information, and switching between tools.</p>
          <p class="text-white/30 text-xs mt-3">Asana &middot; Anatomy of Work Index, 2022</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-ip-navy-surface border border-ip-border rounded-xl p-8">
          <p class="font-serif text-5xl tracking-tight text-white/60 mb-3">103h</p>
          <p class="text-ip-white-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">lost per employee per year to unnecessary meetings. 71% of senior managers say meetings are unproductive and inefficient.</p>
          <p class="text-white/30 text-xs mt-3">Asana &middot; Anatomy of Work, 2021 &amp; HBR &middot; Stop the Meeting Madness, 2017</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-ip-navy-surface border border-ip-border rounded-xl p-8">
          <p class="font-serif text-5xl tracking-tight text-white/60 mb-3">37%</p>
          <p class="text-ip-white-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">of employee time is spent in meetings making decisions &mdash; and more than half of that time is considered ineffective.</p>
          <p class="text-white/30 text-xs mt-3">McKinsey &middot; Decision making in the age of urgency, 2019</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-ip-navy-surface border border-ip-border rounded-xl p-8">
          <p class="font-serif text-5xl tracking-tight text-white/60 mb-3">1.9&times;</p>
          <p class="text-ip-white-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">higher cost and schedule overruns on projects with poor alignment. Misaligned teams waste $1M for every $1B spent.</p>
          <p class="text-white/30 text-xs mt-3">PMI &middot; Pulse of the Profession, 2021</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The Scale Problem -->
  <section class="py-20 md:py-32">
    <div class="container-ip">
      <div class="content-narrow text-center mb-16">
        <p class="section-eyebrow mb-4">Why it compounds</p>
        <h2 class="font-display text-3xl md:text-5xl tracking-tight">
          The tax grows with every layer.
        </h2>
      </div>

      <div class="content-narrow space-y-12">
        <!-- One person -->
        <div class="flex gap-6 items-start">
          <div class="w-12 h-12 rounded-full bg-ip-navy-surface border border-ip-border flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">
            <span class="font-display text-sm text-white">1</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="font-display text-xl mb-2">One person</h3>
            <p class="text-ip-white-muted text-base leading-relaxed">
              You leave a meeting with five things to update — your plan, your task tool, a shared doc, a Slack thread, and your manager's dashboard. You do three. Two drift. Nobody notices until it's a problem.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- One team -->
        <div class="flex gap-6 items-start">
          <div class="w-12 h-12 rounded-full bg-ip-navy-surface border border-ip-border flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">
            <span class="font-display text-sm text-white">8</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="font-display text-xl mb-2">One team</h3>
            <p class="text-ip-white-muted text-base leading-relaxed">
              Eight people in a standup. Decisions happen verbally. Someone writes half of it down. By Thursday, two people think the priority changed. One doesn't know. The plan says something else entirely.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Multiple teams -->
        <div class="flex gap-6 items-start">
          <div class="w-12 h-12 rounded-full bg-ip-navy-surface border border-ip-border flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">
            <span class="font-display text-sm text-white">50+</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="font-display text-xl mb-2">Multiple teams</h3>
            <p class="text-ip-white-muted text-base leading-relaxed">
              Now multiply it. Product decides to deprioritize a feature. Engineering doesn't hear until sprint planning. Sales already promised it to a customer. Finance budgeted for it. Everyone is executing a different version of reality.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="content-narrow mt-16">
        <p class="text-white font-display text-2xl md:text-3xl leading-snug">
          The coordination tax isn't a people problem. It's a systems problem. People can't maintain a shared reality across that many moving parts. They were never supposed to.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The Shift -->
  <section class="py-20 md:py-32 bg-white text-ip-navy">
    <div class="container-ip">
      <div class="content-narrow text-center mb-16">
        <p class="section-eyebrow section-eyebrow--navy mb-4">The shift</p>
        <h2 class="font-display text-3xl md:text-6xl tracking-tight text-ip-navy">
          From tax to layer.
        </h2>
      </div>

      <div class="content-narrow space-y-6 text-ip-navy/70 text-lg leading-relaxed">
        <p>
          The coordination tax exists because coordination was never designed into the system. It's a side effect — something people do <em>on top of</em> the actual work, using tools that were built for something else.
        </p>
        <p>
          The fix isn't another project management tool. It's a <strong class="text-ip-navy">coordination layer</strong> — something that sits underneath your existing tools and meetings, and keeps the shared picture of reality current automatically.
        </p>
        <p>
          Think of it like this:
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="content-narrow grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-12">
        <div class="border border-ip-navy/10 rounded-xl p-8 bg-ip-navy/[0.03]">
          <p class="font-display text-base text-ip-navy/40 mb-4 line-through">Coordination as a tax</p>
          <ul class="space-y-3 text-ip-navy/60 text-sm">
            <li>People manually keep plans up to date</li>
            <li>Meetings are for status, not decisions</li>
            <li>Updates live in someone's head</li>
            <li>Drift is discovered at review time</li>
            <li>Each layer adds more overhead</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="border-2 border-ip-blue rounded-xl p-8 bg-ip-blue/[0.03]">
          <p class="font-display text-base text-ip-blue mb-4">Coordination as a layer</p>
          <ul class="space-y-3 text-ip-navy/80 text-sm">
            <li>The system updates itself from meetings</li>
            <li>Meetings are for decisions and direction</li>
            <li>Changes propagate automatically</li>
            <li>Drift is detected in real time</li>
            <li>Each layer adds more intelligence</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="content-narrow text-ip-navy/70 text-lg leading-relaxed">
        <p>
          When coordination is a layer instead of a tax, managers get their time back. Meetings get shorter. Decisions stick. Everyone works from the same reality — because the system maintains it, not people.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- How In Parallel delivers this -->
  <section class="py-20 md:py-32">
    <div class="container-ip">
      <div class="content-narrow text-center mb-16">
        <p class="section-eyebrow mb-4">How it works</p>
        <h2 class="font-display text-3xl md:text-5xl tracking-tight">
          In Parallel is the coordination layer.
        </h2>
      </div>

      <div class="content-narrow space-y-6 text-ip-white-muted text-lg leading-relaxed mb-16">
        <p>
          It joins your meetings. It listens. It captures every decision, ownership change, and commitment. Then it updates your plan and pushes changes to your connected tools — automatically.
        </p>
        <p>
          No one has to write a status report. No one has to remember what changed. No one has to chase anyone for updates.
        </p>
        <p>
          The plan is always current. The tools are always in sync. Everyone sees the same thing.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="content-narrow grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
        <div class="bg-ip-navy-surface border border-ip-border rounded-xl p-6">
          <p class="font-serif text-3xl tracking-tight text-ip-lime mb-3">6&ndash;8h</p>
          <h3 class="font-display text-base mb-2">saved per person, per week</h3>
          <p class="text-ip-white-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">Your meetings update your plan. Your tasks sync. You never have to reconcile anything manually again.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-ip-navy-surface border border-ip-border rounded-xl p-6">
          <p class="font-serif text-3xl tracking-tight text-ip-lime mb-3">100%</p>
          <h3 class="font-display text-base mb-2">alignment, zero status meetings</h3>
          <p class="text-ip-white-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">Everyone sees the same priorities. Decisions from standups land in the plan immediately. No more &ldquo;I thought we changed that.&rdquo;</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-ip-navy-surface border border-ip-border rounded-xl p-6">
          <p class="font-serif text-3xl tracking-tight text-ip-lime mb-3">2&times;</p>
          <h3 class="font-display text-base mb-2">faster cross-team decisions</h3>
          <p class="text-ip-white-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">Cross-team decisions propagate automatically. When Product reprioritizes, Engineering and Sales see it. No telephone game.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Email capture -->
  <section class="py-16 md:py-24">
    <div class="container-ip">
      <div class="content-narrow">
        <EmailCapture
          source="vision-page"
          heading="Get the full picture"
          description="Insights on coordination intelligence, execution design, and how the best teams actually operate. One email per week."
          buttonText="Subscribe"
          theme="dark"
        />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA -->
  <section class="py-20 md:py-32 bg-ip-navy-light">
    <div class="container-ip text-center">
      <h2 class="font-display text-3xl md:text-6xl tracking-tight mb-6">
        Stop paying the tax.
      </h2>
      <p class="text-ip-white-muted text-lg content-narrow mx-auto mb-10">
        See how In Parallel turns coordination from overhead into advantage. 30-minute demo.
      </p>
      <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row items-center justify-center gap-4">
        <a href="/demo" class="btn-primary">
          Book a demo
          <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M5 12h14M12 5l7 7-7 7"/></svg>
        </a>
        <a href="/#how-it-works" class="btn-secondary">
          See how it works
          <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="currentColor"><polygon points="5,3 19,12 5,21"/></svg>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
